  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Where can I study at Stanford?",
  "response": "Stanford University offers a wide range of academic programs and study spaces across its campus. Here are some key places and resources where you can study at Stanford:\n\n### Academic Buildings and Libraries\n1. **Green Library**\n   - The main library on campus, offering various study spaces, including quiet areas and group study rooms.\n2. **Lathrop Library**\n   - Known for its modern design and collaborative spaces, it's a great place for group work and individual study.\n3. **Terman Engineering Library**\n   - Specifically for engineering students, it provides resources and study spaces tailored to engineering disciplines.\n4. **Meyer Library**\n   - A popular spot for undergraduate students, offering a mix of quiet and collaborative study areas.\n5. **Biology Corner in the Bass Biology Building**\n   - A specialized study space for biology students.\n\n### Study Spaces\n1. **The Huang Engineering Center**\n   - Offers various study spaces, including the d.school, which focuses on design thinking and innovation.\n2. **The Jerry Yang and Akiko Yamazaki Environment and Energy Building (Y2E2)**\n   - Provides study spaces and resources for students interested in environmental and energy studies.\n3. **The Knight Management Center**\n   - Home to the Stanford Graduate School of Business, it offers study spaces for business students.\n4. **The Law School**\n   - Includes the Robert Crown Law Library, which is a resource for law students and faculty.\n\n### Outdoor Study Areas\n1. **Main Quad**\n   - A central and iconic area with benches and grassy areas where students often study.\n2. **The Oval**\n   - A large open space perfect for studying outdoors during good weather.\n3. **Meyer Green**\n   - Adjacent to Meyer Library, it's a popular spot for students to study and relax.\n\n### Special Facilities\n1. **The Stanford Research Park**\n   - While primarily for research and development, it includes resources and spaces that can be utilized by students involved in related projects.\n2. **The Stanford Linear Accelerator Center (SLAC)**\n   - For students involved in physics and related research, SLAC offers unique study and research opportunities.\n\n### Additional Tips\n- **Reserve Study Rooms:** Many libraries and academic buildings allow you to reserve study rooms in advance.\n- **Use Online Resources:** Stanford offers numerous online resources and databases that can be accessed from anywhere on campus.\n- **Join Study Groups:** Many departments and student organizations facilitate study groups that can be a great way to learn and study collaboratively.\n\nTo get the most out of your study time at Stanford, make sure to explore these spaces and find the ones that best suit your study habits and academic needs.",
